document.docTitle: Oisedicus maginus Drohojowska & Szwedo, 2013, sp. n.
document.masterDocTitle: The first Aleyrodidae from the Lowermost Eocene Oise amber (Hemiptera: Sternorrhyncha)

mods:titleInfo.mods:title: The first Aleyrodidae from the Lowermost Eocene Oise amber (Hemiptera: Sternorrhyncha)

subSubSection.paragraph:
Description. Measurements are given in
Table 1
. Antennae 8 -segmented. Antennal segment III twice as long as segment II; IV and V subequal in length. Compound eye distinctly divided; ommatidia in upper portion larger than those in lower portion. Fore wing widened in apical half. Hind wing widened in apical half. Paronychium lingulate; setae of hind tibia evenly dispersed. Claspers tapered in apical half, shifted dorsad, slightly crossed. Aedeagus with small, hook-like apex.
Etymology. Specific epithet from the Proto-Celtic ‘magino’ meaning big, refers to its huge size in comparison with the others.

subSubSection.paragraph: Material. Holotype , male. Specimen No. MNHN PA 2493 , mounted on slide, preserved in Canada balsam. Mesothorax and metathorax covered with gas bubble, apical portion of abdomen and apical portion of hind wing covered with gas bubbles.
